lates funding rates hourly based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices, settling payments automatically through smart contracts. The exchange uses off-chain order matching with on-chain settlement on Starknet, ensuring minimal transaction costs. Funding payments are distributed proportionally to position sizes, with long positions paying shorts when rates are positive and vice versa. Cross-margin functionality allows traders to use unrealized PnL from other positions as collateral for funding rate strategies."}]]}],"$L3",["$L4","$L5","$L6"],"$L7"]}],"$L8"]}]]}],["$L9","$La"],"$Lb"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
3:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","FTM","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FTM/USDT on RabbitX provides opportunities for funding rate arbitrage due to Fantom's volatility and the DEX's competitive fee structure. The 1-hour funding cycles allow for more frequent arbitrage opportunities compared to traditional 8-hour cycles on centralized exchanges. RabbitX's zero gas trading environment makes small funding rate differences profitable that would be uneconomical on other platforms."}]]}]
4:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FTM/USDT funding rates on RabbitX typically range from -0.01% to 0.03% per hour during normal market conditions. During Fantom network upgrades or DeFi protocol launches, rates can spike above 0.05% as retail traders establish long positions. The DEX's smaller user base often results in less efficient funding rate discovery compared to major centralized exchanges, creating arbitrage windows. Correlation analysis shows FTM funding rates tend to follow broader L1 token sentiment, with rates turning negative during general altcoin corrections."}]]}]
5:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between RabbitX and centralized platforms like Binance or OKX can be profitable when funding rate differentials exceed 0.005% per hour. The zero gas fee structure on RabbitX allows traders to enter and exit positions without worrying about Ethereum gas costs eating into profits. Delta-neutral strategies work well during high volatility periods when funding rates diverge significantly from the theoretical rate. Advanced traders can leverage RabbitX's cross-margin system to maintain multiple funding positions across different altcoins simultaneously."}]]}]
6:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"RabbitX's early-stage protocol status presents smart contract risks and potential liquidity constraints during extreme market movements. The limited user base means lower open interest, which can result in higher slippage for larger positions compared to established exchanges. Starknet's L2 dependency introduces additional technical risks, including potential sequencer downtime affecting position management. Funding rate arbitrage strategies should account for RabbitX's 0.02% maker and 0.05% taker fees when calculating profitability thresholds."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lc",null,{"items":[{"question":"What makes RabbitX's 1-hour funding cycles advantageous for FTM arbitrage?","answer":"The shorter cycles provide 8x more arbitrage opportunities compared to standard 8-hour funding periods. This is particularly beneficial for FTM given its volatility patterns and allows traders to capture funding rate inefficiencies more frequently."},{"question":"How does zero gas trading on RabbitX impact FTM funding strategies?","answer":"Zero gas fees make small funding rate differences profitable that would be uneconomical on Ethereum mainnet. This allows traders to execute micro-arbitrage strategies and maintain positions for longer periods without gas cost concerns."},{"question":"What are the liquidity risks for FTM/USDT positions on RabbitX?","answer":"As an early-stage DEX, RabbitX has lower liquidity than major centralized exchanges, potentially causing higher slippage during volatile periods. Traders should size positions appropriately and monitor order book depth before entering large funding arbitrage trades."},{"question":"Can I use cross-margin for FTM funding rate arbitrage on RabbitX?","answer":"Yes, RabbitX's cross-margin system allows you to use unrealized profits from other positions as collateral for FTM trades. This enables more capital-efficient funding strategies and the ability to maintain multiple arbitrage positions simultaneously."}]}]
